---
/*
  /scope — the operational appendix.

  The page that turns "this is a vision" into "this is a fundable
  organization." Three-year milestone schedule, team, budget envelope,
  success metrics, and explicit failure criteria. Written for a funder,
  FRO architect, or program officer who finished the essay and asked
  "ok, what would the org actually look like?"

  Doctrine: this is the document a serious reader earns by reading
  past the manifesto. Operator voice, no promoter voice. Numbers stay
  conservative; failure modes are named first, not buried last.
*/

import Reading from "../layouts/Reading.astro";
import { REPO_URL, HUB_URL } from "../config";
---

<Reading
  title="Scope · Vela"
  description="What a Vela FRO would look like — three-year milestones, team, budget envelope, success metrics, and failure criteria."
  active="scope"
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <p class="eyebrow">Vela · operational appendix</p>
    <h1 class="page-head__title">A Focused Research Organization for scientific state.</h1>
    <p class="page-head__sub">
      Three years, ten million dollars, five to twelve people, one corridor turned into the proof.
      The shape of the org that would turn the protocol into shared infrastructure.
    </p>
  </header>

  <article class="scope">

    <!-- ── Why an FRO, not a startup or a nonprofit ── -->
    <section class="scope__section" aria-labelledby="why-fro">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">00</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="why-fro">Why an FRO is the right vehicle.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>
          The Focused Research Organization model was proposed for projects that fall in the gap
          between academia, startup, industry, and government — time-bound, milestone-driven teams
          building public-good science infrastructure. Vela sits exactly there.
        </p>
        <dl class="scope__pair">
          <dt>A startup</dt>
          <dd>has incentives to enclose the substrate and capture network effects. That kills the
            open-protocol property the entire thesis depends on.</dd>
          <dt>A pure nonprofit</dt>
          <dd>moves at consensus speed. Protocol design needs an authoritative call-maker for the
            first three years.</dd>
          <dt>A university lab</dt>
          <dd>is bound to a PI's funding cycle and graduate-student turnover. Infrastructure of
            this kind needs a five-year horizon and full-time engineers.</dd>
          <dt>A standards body</dt>
          <dd>codifies what already exists. Vela has to ship the implementation first, then let
            stewardship transfer to a long-term home.</dd>
        </dl>
        <p>
          An FRO ships the substrate, runs the proof corridor, recruits the early signers, and
          then sunsets into a foundation, consortium, or stewardship body that maintains the
          protocol after the build phase.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Three-year milestone schedule ── -->
    <section class="scope__section" aria-labelledby="milestones">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">01</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="milestones">Three years, three milestones.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>
          The schedule below is conservative. Each year ends with a publicly verifiable artifact
          and a kill criterion: if the artifact does not exist by the deadline, the project is
          wrong about something load-bearing.
        </p>

        <div class="scope__year">
          <div class="scope__year-head">
            <span class="scope__year-tag">Year 1 · build the corridor</span>
            <span class="scope__year-budget">~$2.0 M · 5 people</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="scope__list">
            <li>Protocol v1.0 frozen and published as a versioned spec.</li>
            <li>Three independent reducer implementations (Rust, Python, TypeScript) agree
              byte-for-byte on a fixed corpus of 500+ findings. <em>(Already true at smaller
              scale; this milestone is hardening, not invention.)</em></li>
            <li>BBB Flagship corridor at 500+ findings, three external reviewer-signers, and
              five worked Correction events that propagated through dependency edges to at
              least one downstream object each.</li>
            <li>Workbench at delight tier — drill-in from any constellation node, hover surfaces
              dependency edges, every finding's evidence chain inspectable in two clicks.</li>
            <li>Public hub stable, mirrored on at least two independent hosts, with a documented
              recovery path if the canonical hub disappears.</li>
            <li>SDK and CLI mature enough that a researcher can deposit their first finding in
              ten minutes without contacting the team.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="scope__kill">
            <strong>Kill criterion:</strong> if month 18 ends with zero external reviewer-signers
            on the BBB corridor, the project is wrong about what scientists want from this layer.
            Stop and reframe before continuing.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="scope__year">
          <div class="scope__year-head">
            <span class="scope__year-tag">Year 2 · five corridors and a journal pilot</span>
            <span class="scope__year-budget">~$3.5 M · 8 people</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="scope__list">
            <li>Five active corridors across different fields. Candidates: oncology
              immunotherapy resistance, longevity plasma proteomics, climate model
              intercomparison, ML reproducibility, antibiotic resistance surveillance.</li>
            <li>Five institutions running their own hub mirrors with at least one writing
              upstream.</li>
            <li>One journal piloting signed Correction events as first-class submissions —
              a 30%-confidence revision should not need a four-page paper to register.</li>
            <li>Fifty+ external signers across all corridors.</li>
            <li>One funder or institutional review board adopts a "deposit before publication"
              policy for a defined class of findings (failed trials, replication attempts,
              null results).</li>
            <li>API ecosystem: at least three third-party tools (a triage app, a
              discriminating-experiment recommender, a confidence dashboard) built against the
              hub by people not on the team.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="scope__kill">
            <strong>Kill criterion:</strong> if month 30 ends with no journal or funder
            integrated, the political coalition is not real and a different organization needs
            to carry that work.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="scope__year">
          <div class="scope__year-head">
            <span class="scope__year-tag">Year 3 · field tipping and handoff</span>
            <span class="scope__year-budget">~$4.0 M · 10–12 people</span>
          </div>
          <ul class="scope__list">
            <li>Ten or more corridors live; one hundred or more external signers.</li>
            <li>Self-sustaining open contributor base — the protocol gets pull requests from
              outside the FRO every week.</li>
            <li>One field pivot: a major funder allocates against the live frontier rather
              than against a citation count.</li>
            <li>Stewardship handoff: the FRO sunsets into a long-term maintainer (foundation,
              consortium, or absorbed into an existing open-science institution) with the
              protocol decision rights, hub responsibility, and contributor norms transferred
              cleanly.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="scope__total">
          Three-year envelope: roughly <strong>$10 M</strong>, conservative for an FRO of this
          ambition. Comparable infrastructure projects (the early Protein Data Bank, arXiv,
          Galaxy Project) ran longer with less, but had different cost structures and predated
          the AI inflection that makes this layer urgent.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Team ── -->
    <section class="scope__section" aria-labelledby="team">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">02</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="team">The team that ships year one.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>
          Five people, full-time, twelve months. Each role is named for what it has to deliver,
          not what it has to perform.
        </p>
        <dl class="scope__pair">
          <dt>Founder · protocol architect</dt>
          <dd>Owns the protocol design, makes the hard calls about what stays open vs.
            implementation-defined, writes the spec, defends the kill criteria. Will Blair in
            this role for year one.</dd>
          <dt>Senior research engineer · Rust + distributed systems</dt>
          <dd>Owns the reducer implementations, hub reliability, signature scheme hardening,
            local-first sync, and the byte-identical replay guarantee. The single most
            load-bearing engineering hire.</dd>
          <dt>Frontend engineer · workbench + viz</dt>
          <dd>Owns the workbench, the constellation viz, the deposit flow, and every surface a
            non-engineer scientist sees. Polish-tier work; the workbench has to feel like
            Linear or Figma, not like a PI's side project.</dd>
          <dt>Reviewer-in-residence · credentialed Alzheimer's-corridor scientist</dt>
          <dd>Owns the BBB Flagship corridor: curates findings, recruits and onboards external
            reviewer-signers, defends the editorial standard. Without this role the corridor
            cannot reach external trust.</dd>
          <dt>Operations + community lead</dt>
          <dd>Owns docs, contributor onboarding, partnership conversations, hub reliability
            ops, and the boring work that turns "interesting project" into "thing other
            institutions can adopt without negotiation."</dd>
        </dl>
        <p>
          Year two adds a second research engineer (multi-corridor scaling, API ecosystem),
          a second reviewer-in-residence (the second corridor), and a partnerships lead
          (journal + funder integrations). Year three adds the long-term stewardship hire.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Success metrics ── -->
    <section class="scope__section" aria-labelledby="success">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">03</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="success">What success looks like, measured.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>Three categories, one set of receipts each. None of them are "users" in the SaaS sense.</p>
        <dl class="scope__pair">
          <dt>Receipts</dt>
          <dd>External signers per corridor. Worked Correction events landed. Downstream
            pipelines (trials, reviews, target hypotheses) updated automatically by a
            propagated Correction. These are the only metrics that prove the substrate moves
            real decisions.</dd>
          <dt>Adoption</dt>
          <dd>Hub mirrors run by other institutions. Hub API queries per week from clients
            we did not build. Third-party tools integrating against the hub. These prove the
            protocol is acting like infrastructure, not like an in-house system.</dd>
          <dt>Field impact</dt>
          <dd>Trials whose enrollment criteria changed in response to a propagated Correction.
            Funders who reallocated against the live frontier. Journals that accepted signed
            Correction events as first-class submissions. These are slow to arrive and the
            ones the project is actually for.</dd>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Failure modes ── -->
    <section class="scope__section" aria-labelledby="failure">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">04</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="failure">Where this is most likely to fail.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>
          Three failure modes are real enough to name first. Each has a kill criterion above;
          this section explains why the criterion exists.
        </p>
        <dl class="scope__pair">
          <dt>Reviewer recruitment</dt>
          <dd>The hardest problem in year one is not technical. Convincing a credentialed
            scientist to be the reviewer-in-residence — and to recruit other reviewers to
            sign findings into a substrate that does not yet count for tenure — depends on
            credit reform that we cannot ship from inside the FRO. We can prove the technical
            substrate works; we cannot prove the social substrate exists until someone with
            existing credibility says yes.</dd>
          <dt>The "another GitHub for science" trap</dt>
          <dd>Fifteen years of failed attempts have made every reviewer skeptical. The
            differentiator is the writeable, signed, content-addressed primitives — but if
            the workbench feels like a generic upload form, the project gets pattern-matched
            to BioRxiv-with-extra-steps and dies on first impression. The bar for the workbench
            is correspondingly higher than the technical work alone would suggest.</dd>
          <dt>Capture by a single AI lab</dt>
          <dd>The strongest funders for this work — OpenAI Foundation, Arc, large pharma AI
            programs — have incentives to wrap the substrate in a proprietary layer the
            moment it becomes useful. The protocol design and the FRO governance both have
            to make capture either impossible or pointless. Local-first by default, signed
            events portable across hubs, the canonical reducer open-source — these are the
            structural defenses, not aspirational principles.</dd>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Closing ── -->
    <section class="scope__section scope__section--close" aria-labelledby="now">
      <header class="scope__head">
        <span class="scope__num">05</span>
        <h2 class="scope__title" id="now">Why this gets built now.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="scope__body">
        <p>
          The window is short. AI labs are producing scientific work faster than any prior
          generation of tools, and every output that lands in a private log instead of a
          shared record is a public good lost. The substrate either gets built as open
          protocol in the next two to three years or it gets built as proprietary layers
          that every model has to license to function.
        </p>
        <p>
          Infrastructure of this kind is built once a generation. The people who finish it
          are usually not the people who started it. The job of the FRO is to start it well
          enough that someone else can finish it.
        </p>
        <p class="scope__cta">
          Read the essay at
          <a class="inline-link" href="https://borrowedlight.org" rel="noopener">borrowedlight.org</a>.
          See the protocol at <a class="inline-link" href="/protocol">/protocol</a>.
          See what isn't true yet at <a class="inline-link" href="/honest">/honest</a>.
          Open the workbench at <a class="inline-link" href="/workbench">/workbench</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

  </article>
</Reading>

<style>
  .scope { max-width: 64rem; margin: 0 auto; }

  .scope__section {
    border-top: 1px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 32%, transparent);
    padding: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-6);
  }
  .scope__section--close {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-2);
  }
  .scope__head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 14px;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  .scope__num {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 13px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 72%, var(--ink-2));
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .scope__title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 450;
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2.8vw, 2rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.018em;
    color: var(--ink-0);
    margin: 0;
    text-wrap: balance;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 96, "SOFT" 30;
  }
  .scope__body p {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.62;
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--ink-1) 90%, var(--ink-2));
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
    max-width: 64ch;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  .scope__body p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  .scope__pair {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 16rem 1fr;
    gap: 0.85rem var(--space-5);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: 0;
  }
  .scope__pair dt {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.94rem;
    color: var(--ink-0);
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
  }
  .scope__pair dd {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.96rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-1);
    margin: 0;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .scope__pair { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.3rem var(--space-3); }
    .scope__pair dt { margin-top: 0.6rem; }
    .scope__pair dt:first-of-type { margin-top: 0; }
  }

  .scope__year {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-5);
    padding: 1.2rem 1.4rem 1.4rem;
    background: var(--paper-1);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-2);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  .scope__year-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    padding-bottom: 0.7rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-1);
  }
  .scope__year-tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 76%, var(--ink-2));
  }
  .scope__year-budget {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    color: var(--ink-3);
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }
  .scope__list {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
    padding: 0 0 0 1.2rem;
    list-style: disc;
  }
  .scope__list li {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.96rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-1);
    margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  .scope__kill {
    margin: 0 !important;
    padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--cinnabar) 6%, var(--paper-0));
    border-left: 2px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--cinnabar) 48%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-size: 0.92rem !important;
    color: var(--ink-1) !important;
  }
  .scope__total {
    margin-top: var(--space-4) !important;
    padding-top: var(--space-3);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule-1);
  }
  .scope__cta {
    margin-top: var(--space-4) !important;
    font-size: 0.96rem;
  }
  .inline-link {
    color: var(--ink-1);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 56%, transparent);
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
    transition: color var(--dur-1) var(--ease), text-decoration-color var(--dur-1) var(--ease);
  }
  .inline-link:hover {
    color: var(--gold);
    text-decoration-color: var(--gold);
  }
</style>
